Reference for 9front awk(1): pattern-action language; fields $1..$NF; built-in variables FS NR NF etc; all built-in functions; BEGIN/END; -F -v -f -safe flags.

# 9front awk(1) — pattern-directed scanning and processing language

## Synopsis

    awk [-F fs] [-d] [-safe] [-v var=value] [-f progfile | prog] [file ...]

## Description

awk scans each input file line by line, matching each line against the
pattern of every pattern-action statement, and executing the action for
each match.  The filename - means stdin.  A file argument of the form
var=value is treated as a variable assignment executed when that file
would have been opened.

## Flags

    -F fs       Set the input field separator to regexp fs.
    -v var=val  Set variable var before program execution. Repeatable.
    -f progfile Read the awk program from progfile instead of prog.
    -safe       Safe mode: no shell commands, no file opens, no ENVIRON.
    -d          (debug) dump parsing information.

## Program structure

A program is a sequence of pattern-action statements:

    pattern { action }

A missing action defaults to { print }.  A missing pattern always matches.
Statements are separated by newlines or semicolons.

Special patterns:
    BEGIN   { ... }   executed before any input is read
    END     { ... }   executed after all input is exhausted

Range pattern:
    pat1, pat2  { ... }   action applied to all lines from the first line
                          matching pat1 through the next line matching pat2.

## Fields and records

Each input line is a record.  Fields are split by FS (default: whitespace).
    $0      entire record
    $1..$NF individual fields (NF is the number of fields)
    $(NF)   last field
    $0 = "..." reassigning $0 re-splits into fields

If FS is empty (""), each character becomes a separate field.

## Built-in variables

    FS        input field separator regexp (default whitespace)
    RS        input record separator (default newline)
    OFS       output field separator (default space)
    ORS       output record separator (default newline)
    NR        current record number (cumulative across files)
    FNR       current record number within the current file
    NF        number of fields in current record
    FILENAME  name of current input file
    OFMT      output format for numbers (default "%.6g")
    CONVFMT   format for internal number-to-string conversion (default "%.6g")
    SUBSEP    multi-subscript separator (default \034)
    ARGC      argument count (assignable)
    ARGV      argument array (assignable; non-null members used as file names)
    ENVIRON   array of environment variables (not in -safe mode)

## Statements

    if (expr) stmt [else stmt]
    while (expr) stmt
    for (init; cond; incr) stmt
    for (var in array) stmt
    do stmt while (expr)
    break
    continue
    { stmt ... }
    expression          (assignment is a common expression statement)
    print [list] [> file | >> file | | cmd]
    printf format [, list] [> file | >> file | | cmd]
    return [expr]
    next              skip remaining patterns on this line; read next input
    nextfile          skip rest of current file; open next; restart at top
    delete array[expr]
    delete array
    exit [expr]       exit immediately; status is expr

## Operators

Arithmetic: + - * / % ^ (exponentiation)
String:     concatenation (whitespace between expressions)
Assignment: = += -= *= /= %= ^=
Comparison: == != < <= > >=
Logical:    && || !
Ternary:    expr ? expr : expr
Increment:  ++ --
Match:      ~ (matches regexp)  !~ (does not match regexp)
Array test: (i) in array

## Regular expressions

Used as patterns and in ~ / !~ operators.  Plan 9 regexp(6) syntax.
/re/ is a constant regexp; a string variable may also be used as a regexp
except in bare pattern position.

## Built-in functions

### String functions
    length(s)           length of string s (or array s = number of elements;
                        no arg = length of $0)
    substr(s, m)        substring of s starting at position m (1-based)
    substr(s, m, n)     n-character substring starting at m
    index(s, t)         position of string t in s, or 0
    match(s, r)         position of regexp r in s, or 0; sets RSTART and RLENGTH
    split(s, a, fs)     split s into array a using fs; return count
                        (fs defaults to FS; empty fs splits per character)
    sub(r, t [, s])     replace first match of regexp r with t in s (default $0)
                        & in t = matched text; returns number of replacements
    gsub(r, t [, s])    replace all matches of r with t; return count
    sprintf(fmt, ...)   format string (same as printf format)
    tolower(str)        convert to lower case
    toupper(str)        convert to upper case

### I/O functions
    print [list]        print to stdout (OFS between items, ORS at end)
    printf fmt [, list] formatted print (C printf-style, see fprintf(2))
    getline             read next record from input into $0; return 1/0/-1
    getline < file      read next record from file into $0
    getline x           read next record from input into variable x
    getline x < file    read from file into x
    cmd | getline       pipe cmd output; each call returns next line
    close(expr)         close file or pipe expr
    fflush([expr])      flush file/pipe expr (or all if omitted/empty)
    system(cmd)         execute cmd; return its exit status

### Math functions
    atan2(y, x)
    cos(x)
    sin(x)
    exp(x)
    log(x)
    sqrt(x)
    int(x)              truncate to integer
    rand()              random number in (0,1)
    srand([seed])       set rand seed; return previous seed

### Plan 9 specific
    utf(n)              convert character number n to a UTF string

## User-defined functions

    function name(p1, p2, ...) { ...; return expr }

Parameters are passed by value for scalars, by reference for arrays.
All other variables are global.  Extra parameters serve as local variables.
Functions may be recursive.

## Arrays

Associative arrays with string subscripts:
    a["key"] = val
    a[i,j]             multi-subscript: indices joined with SUBSEP
    delete a[key]
    delete a            delete all elements
    for (k in a)        iterate over all keys
    (k) in a            test membership

## Examples

Print lines longer than 72 characters:
    awk 'length($0) > 72'

Print first two fields in reversed order:
    awk '{ print $2, $1 }'

Use comma-or-whitespace field separator:
    awk 'BEGIN { FS = ",[ \t]*|[ \t]+" } { print $2, $1 }'

Sum first column and print total and average:
    awk '{ s += $1 } END { print "sum", s, "avg", s/NR }'

Print all lines between /start/ and /stop/:
    awk '/start/,/stop/'

Count occurrences of each word:
    awk '{ for (i=1; i<=NF; i++) count[$i]++ } END { for (w in count) print count[w], w }' | sort -rn

Simulate echo:
    awk 'BEGIN { for (i=1; i<ARGC; i++) printf "%s ", ARGV[i]; printf "\n"; exit }' a b c

Print lines where field 3 > 100:
    awk '$3 > 100'

Strip comments (lines beginning with #):
    awk '!/^#/'

In-place substitution (no -i on 9front; use a temp file):
    awk '{ gsub(/old/, "new"); print }' file > file.tmp && mv file.tmp file

## Differences from POSIX awk (and GNU gawk)

**Regexp engine:** Uses Plan 9 regexp(6), not POSIX ERE.  No POSIX character
classes ([[:alpha:]], [[:digit:]] etc.), no interval expressions ({m,n}), no
\b \d \w \s shorthand, no backreferences.  Alternation | and grouping () work
as in ERE.

**-safe flag:** The -safe flag (disable file I/O, shell commands, and
ENVIRON) is a 9front/Plan 9 extension not in POSIX or gawk.

**-d flag:** The -d flag enables parser debug output.  Not in POSIX.

**-F t tab wart:** -Ft and -F t (the letter t alone) are silently rewritten
to a literal tab character.  POSIX requires using -F '\t' or a C escape;
this wart preserves Plan 9 convention.

**utf() function:** The utf(n) built-in (convert a Unicode code point to a
UTF-8 string) is a Plan 9 extension with no POSIX equivalent.

**nextfile statement:** The nextfile statement (skip remaining records of the
current file and proceed to the next) is a common extension; it was not in
the original POSIX spec (added later in POSIX 2008 as an optional extension).

**delete array:** delete array (delete all elements of an array at once) is a
common extension not in original POSIX awk.

**Pipes to getline:** The cmd | getline form (pipe a shell command's output
into getline) is a common extension; POSIX added it in later revisions.

**Shell commands use rc(1):** system(cmd) and all pipe operations ( | cmd,
cmd | getline) run commands via /bin/rc, not /bin/sh.  Scripts using
sh-specific syntax will fail silently or produce wrong results.

**No gensub():** The gensub(re, repl, how [, str]) function (GNU awk
extension for capturing groups in replacements via \1..\9) is absent.
Use multiple sub/gsub calls instead.

**No OFMT/printf %* width:** printf format widths from variables (%*d) may
or may not be supported; test before relying on them.

**No BEGINFILE / ENDFILE:** GNU awk's BEGINFILE and ENDFILE special patterns
are absent.

**No @include / @load:** GNU awk's @include and @load directives are absent.

**No -M arbitrary precision:** GNU awk's -M (MPFR arbitrary precision) flag
is absent; all arithmetic is double-precision floating point.

**No multiple -f files sharing state:** Multiple -f progfiles are concatenated
into a single program, which matches gawk behavior, but POSIX only requires
one -f.  On 9front the limit is 20 -f files (pfile[20] in the source).

**Number formatting:** OFMT and CONVFMT default to "%.6g", same as POSIX.
Output format for integers printed via print is plain decimal (no %.6g
applied to exact integers).

**RS multi-character:** RS is only honoured as a single character (the first
character of the string).  GNU awk treats RS as a regexp when it is more
than one character.

**Associative array iteration order:** for (k in a) iterates in an
unspecified (hash-table-dependent) order, same as POSIX — but programs that
assume sorted or insertion order will behave differently from gawk with
PROCINFO["sorted_in"].

**ENVIRON unavailable in -safe mode:** POSIX does not define -safe; scripts
that rely on ENVIRON and are run under -safe will see an empty array.

**UTF-8 handling:** The source notes that UTF is not always handled correctly,
though an attempt is made.  split() with an empty FS copes with UTF in the
string being split.  Byte-level patterns on multi-byte characters may give
unexpected results.

